  <!-- PAGE 0: WHY INVEST -->
  <div class="section-page active" id="page-0">
    <div class="hero">
      <div class="section-num">Module 01 of 07</div>
      <div class="section-title">Why Should You Invest?</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">Your salary is a starting point, not a destination. Here's why sitting on cash is the riskiest thing you can do.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="content-body">
      <div class="highlight highlight-red">
        <strong>The uncomfortable truth:</strong> If your money is sitting in a bank account earning 1–2% interest, you are losing purchasing power every year. Indonesian inflation runs at 2–4% annually. UK inflation has averaged 3–4% over the last decade. You are getting poorer in real terms.
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">💡 The Power of Compounding</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          Compounding is when your returns generate their own returns. A $10,000 investment at 10% annual return becomes <strong>$67,275 in 20 years</strong> — without adding another penny. At 15%, it becomes <strong>$163,665</strong>. Time in the market is your most powerful asset.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">📊 BSJ Context — Where You Actually Are</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          On your monthly salary, most teachers have enough to invest meaningfully after living costs. The question isn't whether you can afford to invest — it's whether you can afford not to. Jakarta's low cost of living relative to salary is a genuine advantage most expats underuse.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight highlight-gold">
        <strong>The goal:</strong> Build passive income streams that eventually replace your need to work. Even $500/month in passive income changes your options significantly. $3,000–5,000/month gives you genuine freedom.
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">⚠️ What Investing Is NOT</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          Investing is not gambling — though it can become that without discipline. It is not a get-rich-quick scheme. It is not complicated once you understand the basics. And it is not something to defer until you feel "ready." The best time to start was 10 years ago. The second best time is now.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
