      <div class="section-num">Module 06 of 07</div>
      <div class="section-title">Your First Investment</div>
      <div class="section-subtitle">Practical guidance on what to buy first, how much, and the habits that separate successful investors from everyone else.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="content-body">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">🏁 Start Simple</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          Your first investment should be Bitcoin. Not because it's the most exciting, but because it's the most understood, the most liquid, and the most proven store of value in crypto. Once you have Bitcoin and understand how it behaves, you can diversify into ETH, SOL, and others.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">📅 Dollar Cost Averaging (DCA)</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          DCA means investing a fixed amount at regular intervals regardless of price. Instead of trying to time the market (which professionals consistently fail to do), you invest $200 every month whether BTC is at $50,000 or $80,000. Over time, this averages your cost basis and removes emotion from the equation. <strong>It is the single most effective strategy for most investors.</strong>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight highlight-gold">
        <strong>Suggested starting allocation (moderate risk):</strong> 50% BTC, 25% ETH, 15% SOL, 10% cash reserve. As your confidence grows and you understand each asset, adjust. Never invest money you need in the next 12 months.
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">🔒 The Habits That Matter</div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p style="margin-bottom:8px"><strong>1. Never sell in a panic.</strong> Every major crypto crash has been followed by a new all-time high. The losers are people who sold.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:8px"><strong>2. Keep records.</strong> Track every purchase date, amount, and price. You'll need this for tax purposes and to understand your actual returns.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:8px"><strong>3. Don't check prices hourly.</strong> Set a weekly review time. Obsessive price-checking leads to poor decisions.</p>
          <p><strong>4. Cold storage for significant holdings.</strong> Once you hold more than $5,000 in crypto, move the majority to a hardware wallet (Ledger, Trezor). Exchange hacks do happen.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight highlight-red">
        <strong>Never do this:</strong> Don't invest borrowed money. Don't buy obscure altcoins based on Telegram tips. Don't share your account details or seed phrase with anyone. Don't invest your emergency fund.
      </div>
    </div>
